    jemalloc, dlmalloc and tlsf are all interesting allocators that should be explored.

    Using these allocators I should be able to implement proper heirarchical heaps.

    Right now I suspect that jemalloc may be the winner.

    Need to think about multithreaded allocations as well. What is the strategy?

    ----------------------------------

    When I am in a katamari ball and I press SPACE I want to burst
    out of it and go up high. Right now it is very unsatisfying!

    ^--- solve by extra force proportional to velocity, eg. if
    velocity is below a certain amount of up (faded out), add extra
    up force, this should apply extra up force to remove the weight
    of the other stones that are pushing down on you.

    ^--- extra up force should only apply if within say, 1-2m of ground.

    When I bounce on the ground, I would like there to be a region,
    say 1-2m worth, where I have the same consistent launch up force
    vs. right now where it feels there is a small 25cm area where I 
    get a big force up.

    When I accelerate the ball left/right I would like it to do so
    a bit faster initially when I am still, eg. an amount of extra force
    proportional to the dot of my speed in the direction I want to go.

    When I roll really quickly I want the cubes I splash through to be
    pushed forward with some force proportional to my linear velocity,
    eg. if linear velocity is above some threshold, add a force proportional
    to that speed in the direction of motion to push or splash cubes forward.

    ----------------------------------

    It would be much better to do the stencil shadows in a vertex shader instead!

